<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><listPerson xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><person xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xml:id="CAR02" sex="1"><persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><roleName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Major</roleName><forename xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">John</forename><surname xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Cartwright</surname><addName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/></persName><birth xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1740-09-17"><placeName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"> </placeName></birth><death xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1824-09-23"/><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">political reformer</occupation><occupation xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/><note xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="editorial"><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Cartwright joined the navy in 1758 and had a successful career. He returned to England in 1770 and began to read widely and write profusely. He developed 
      sympathy - which he professed in writing  - for the American 
    colonists which caused him to refuse a commission in American waters in 1775. This ended his naval career but he continued to campaign for political reform. He became a member 
    of the Society of Friends of the People. A testament to his lifelong struggle for the reform of parliament was his arrest for sedition in 1821 at the age of eighty-one.
    </p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">We have coded all instances of 'Major Cartwright' as Major John Cartwright.
    There are other instances of 'Cartwright' in the diary. One feature about the entries is that there is a
    consistent link prior to 1811, with artists: The first call is with <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="BAR01">Barry</persName>; the second is at
    <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="JOH01">Johnson's</persName> with <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="FUS01">Fuseli</persName>; the third is at the <title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">Milton Gallery</title> with 
    <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="OPI01">Opie</persName>, <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="LAW01">Lawrence</persName>, Barry and others;
    and the fourth and fifth also at Johnson's with Fuesli. We have coded these entries as the artist <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="CAR05">John Cartwright</persName> who shared a house with Fuseli for a number
    of years and was influenced by him.</p><p xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">This leaves us with an unidentified final entry under Cartwright,
    where both the painter and reformer are dead. But that Cartwright seems to be someone with whom
    <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="SHE02">Mary Shelly</persName> is acting as an intermediary in 1826 - possibly someone in the book trade. This
    Cartright has been left uncoded, along with rev.Cartwright, whom he meets once at <persName xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" key="TOO01">Horne
    Tooke's</persName>, and Miss Cartwright, whom he also meets just one.</p></note><bibl xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="other"><title xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">DNB</title></bibl><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="appearancesInDiary"><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1788"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1789"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1790"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1791"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1792"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1793"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1794"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1795"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1796"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1797"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1798"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1799"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1799-07-28" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1800"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1801"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1802"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1803"><date xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" when="1803-02-23" n="notVenue" type="ah"/></ab><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1804"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1805"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1806"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1807"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1808"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1809"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1810"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1811"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1812"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1813"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1814"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1815"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1816"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1817"/><ab xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" n="1818"/><ab xmln